    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-20T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-20T13:00:00-05:00" n="565"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d565">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/5–2054: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">United States Delegation</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-20T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 20, 1954—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 93. Repeated information Paris 208. Eyes
                    only Ambassador. Reference <gloss target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 86, repeated
                    information Paris 295.<note n="1" xml:id="d565fn1">Dated May 19, <ref
                            target="#pg_853">p. 853</ref>.</note> While not happy about situation,
                        <persName corresp="#p_BG1">Bidault</persName> agrees that for time being
                    talks should continue in Paris on understanding he will be kept closely informed
                    here. He was worried at receiving no news from Paris of talks in last few days,
                    but felt better when I told him we had heard of none and were sure there had
                    been none. He was concerned about intrigue there, while expressing complete
                    confidence in integrity of <persName corresp="#p_LJ1">Laniel</persName> and
                        <persName corresp="#p_SM1">Maurice Schumann</persName>, he appears to feel
                    that his political antennae are more sensitive than theirs. He mentioned one
                    mechanical problem in that <persName corresp="#p_JDMR1">Margerie</persName> was
                    only one in Quai d’Orsay at working level whom he trusted to backstop these
                    conversations satisfactorily, but felt he could not spare him from Geneva. He
                    believes that it should be fairly clear by end of next week whether there is any
                    chance of doing any serious negotiating here and if prospect is then negative,
                    he hopes to turn over to <persName corresp="#p_SM1">Schumann</persName> and
                    return to Paris.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
